Severe malformation of the basement membrane and neuronal migration consisting of cobblestone cortex, abnormal white matter, enlarged ventricles (often with hydrocephalus), small brain stem and small dysplastic cerebellum. In the most severely affected patients the brain surface is smooth, which led to the designation as lissencephaly, although less severe cobblestone malformations have an irregular, pebbled surface rather than a smooth surface.
syndrome_name: Congenital disorder of glycosylation type II

phenotype_description: Severe malformation of the basement membrane and neuronal migration consisting of cobblestone cortex, abnormal white matter, enlarged ventricles (often with hydrocephalus), small brain stem and small dysplastic cerebellum. In the most severely affected patients the brain surface is smooth, which led to the designation as lissencephaly, although less severe cobblestone malformations have an irregular, pebbled surface rather than a smooth surface.
syndrome_features: Congenital muscular dystrophy, congenital contractures (usually at the elbows), severe CNS dysgenesis (cobblestone malformation, pontine hypoplasia, Dandy-Walker malformation), eye malformations (including coarse trabecular meshwork in anterior chamber resulting in glaucoma, progressive retinal atrophy, congenital or juvenile cataracts, microphthalmia, buphthalmus, Peter anomaly)
syndrome_synonyms: HARD Syndrome (Hydrocephalus, Agyria, and Retinal Dysplasia), Cerebroocular dysgenesis, Cerebroocular dysplasia-muscular dystrophy syndrome

In the most severely affected patients the brain surface is smooth, which led to the designation as lissencephaly, although less severe cobblestone malformations have an irregular, pebbled surface rather than a smooth surface.

phenotype_description: Focal cortical dysplasias form a broad spectrum of malformations of cortical development. Type I FCDs are associated with architectural disturbances of the radial arrangement (type Ia) or tangential arrangement (Ib) of cortical neurons, or both (Ic). Type I FCDs are thought to result from late prenatal, perinatal, or early postnatal insults. When FCD type I is associated with other findings, they are termed type III (IIIa = with hippocampal sclerosis, IIIb = with glial tumors, IIIc = vascular malformations, IIId = scarring from extrinsic injury). Type II FCDs have dysmorphic neurons (IIa) and balloon cells (IIb) and are thought to arise from earlier genetic disturbances.

A malformation of the brainstem and cerebellum that resembles a tooth when seen on axial MRI. Characterized by 1) Hypoplastic, high-lying cerebellar vermis (best seen on sagittal midline view) 2) Deficiency of the dorsal midbrain with a narrow isthmus and abnormally deep interpeduncular fossa (seen on axial view) 3) Large, elongated cerebellar peduncles (seen on axial view).
syndrome_features: Abnormal eye movements, neonatal disordered breathing (tachypnea, hyperpnea, central apnea), molar tooth malformation

syndrome_features: Abnormal eye movements, neonatal disordered breathing (tachypnea, hyperpnea, central apnea), molar tooth malformation

phenotype_description: Combination of cerebellar vermis hypoplasia, absence of middle cerebellar peduncles, flattened ventral pons, vaulted pontine tegmentum, molar tooth aspect of the pontomesencephalic junction, and absent inferior olivary prominence.
Fusion of the cerebellar hemispheres, with absence or hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis and fusion of the cerebellar dentate nuclei and superior cerebellar peduncles.

A malformation of cortical development caused by the failure of a subpopulation of migrating neurons to reach the developing cortical plate. The heterotopic neurons form a bilateral, symmetric band of gray matter located below the cortical ribbon and separated from it by a thin band of white matter.

A malformation of cortical development caused by the failure of a subpopulation of migrating neurons to reach the developing cortical plate. The heterotopic neurons form a bilateral, symmetric band of gray matter located below the cortical ribbon and separated from it by a thin band of white matter.
Clefts lined with gray matter that extend through the entire cerebral mantle, from the ependymal lining of the lateral ventricles to the pial covering of the cortex.
Hamartomas that tend to be located along the ventricular surface of the caudate nucleus, most often on the lamina of the sulcus thalamostriatus immediately posterior to the foramen of Monro.
syndrome_features: Hypopigmented macules ("ash-leaf spots"), facial angiofibromas, shagreen patches, ungual fibromas, cortical tubers, developmental delay, renal angiomyolipomas, cardiac rhabdomyomas
syndrome_synonyms: Tuberous Sclerosis type 1, Tuberous Sclerosis type 2, Bourneville Disease

phenotype_description: Hamartomatous nodules that may appear as enlarged, atypically shaped gyri. Histologically, they consist of bizarre giant cells, dense fibrillary gliosis, and diminished, disordered myelin sheaths. Balloon cells may be seen, making tubers histologically indistinguishable from focal cortical dysplasia.
